nglaterra, United Kingdom":"Cadbury, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"Abt 1165–1227":"about 1165–1227","1165–1227":"1165–1227","1175–1219":"1175–1219","1195–1264":"1195–1264","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1140–1166":"1140–1166","1146–Female":"1146–Deceased","1264":"1264","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1140":"1140","1195":"1195","1193":"1193","1227":"1227","Abt 1195":"about 1195","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1146":"1146","1200":"1200","Abt 1165":"about 1165","1166":"1166","1219":"1219","Lewe, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","England":"England","Cadbury, Devon, Inglaterra, United Kingdom":"Cadbury, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Meulles","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  Scottish:  see  Mellis  .","2  English: locative name from Mellis (Suffolk)."],"variants":[{"name":"Mellis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Greek Spiro, Christos, Spero.","Scottish (mainly Aberdeenshire and Morayshire): from an Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Maol Íosa</i> ‘devotee of Jesus’.","Greek: variant of   Melis  ."]},{"name":"Mells","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived in a place where there was more than one mill, Middle English <i>melles</i> ‘mills’, or a habitational name for someone from Mells in Somerset, named with this word."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":50,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":59,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger Meulles (2 Sons) was born about 1165, in Devon, England, his father, Juhel Molis (2 Sons), was 26 and his mother, Mrs. Joellus Molis, was 20. He married Roesia in 1193, in Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1227, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 63, and was buried in England."},"et":{"Abt 1165–1227":"umbes 1165–1227","1165–1227":"1165–1227","1175–1219":"1175–1219","1195–1264":"1195–1264","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1140–1166":"1140–1166","1146–Female":"1146–Surnud","1264":"1264","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1140":"1140","1195":"1195","1193":"1193","1227":"1227","Abt 1195":"umbes 1195","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1146":"1146","1200":"1200","Abt 1165":"u